            "reviewBody": "Slow and steady wins the race. These were a big hit"
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "WestfW"
            },
            "reviewBody": "I wonder if you can say something about the DEPTH of onions in the pan during the browning phase. In my experience, if the depth is too shallow, the onions can dry out and get crispy, or blacken. If you have too many onions, then the onions on top get more steamed than carmelized (even with stirring), and you end up with unevenly caramelized onions. This is problematic, since the volume of onions decreases as they cook.\n(Of course, my experience is somewhat limited, and my results could also be due to wrong temperature or insufficient stirring.)"
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "MarkT29"
            },
            "reviewBody": "I don't know if I did something wrong or there's a typo in the yield above, but I started with 3lb onions and got 1.5 cups of caramelized onions, not a quart."
        }
